The feeling of being in a moment like this is exactly why I love hiking. The struggle and uncertainty on the way there. The occasional rain, stepping in dirt, thorns flung into your face.

Then you see it. The view. The peak. The rainbow over the view you’ve dreamed of. Suddenly all the struggles are replaced by a euphoric feeling of accomplishment and gratitude.

Standing proud and free. The outdoors, hiking specifically, has saved me in so many ways. Nature has been my teacher, my friend, my escape, nature is me. Nature is a part of us, we are a part of nature.

I think the smile on my face says it all. Life’s a climb. We go through shiz, sometimes we step in it, sometimes it freaking sucks, but it’s all there to build our grit, teach us things, strengthen us, and ultimately prepare us. For wild things beyond our imagination. 

Perfectly imperfect. Sitting in the Kauai airport physically exhausted but emotionally riding a high. So grateful for this life. This life is a blessing. Mahalo Hawaii. Always so grateful. 🫶🏽

One of the greatest realizations of my life came when I learned to understand that true luxury, true freedom, wealth even, is a mindset. My mentor Tony Robbins shares that financial freedom without emotional freedom is the ultimate failure. What does a life of luxury look like for you? I’m currently reading “Think and Grow Rich” and one of the reflection prompts is how would your life change if you had a million dollars. And upon journaling on it, I realized my lifestyle would look exactly as it does now with just a few differences. What money, namely wealth provides you is the freedom to choose. What “wealth” in mindset provides you is the opportunity to look in to your life from an outside perspective with gratitude for all it is, and consciously create. Society makes us believe that to deserve to be alive we must slave away, be stressed, be unhappy, grind, reach burnout all the time. But I’m here to tell you that’s not true. Let’s normalize living a life you actually love because you are a human being and you deserve that. You don’t have to be stressed all the time. You don’t have to hate your life to fit in to society’s narrative. You can live a life you genuinely love. It’s out there. 

My questions for you: 
- how would your life change with a million dollars? 
- how can you take steps to make that your reality? 
- what does wealth mean to you? 

Live it ✨

When I graduated from college and started working as a Big 4 Consultant I’d fly 2x/week commuting from Washington DC to Chicago. Almost every single flight the person next to me was an older person who would just start sharing all their life regrets with me. One of my strong suits is listening which has been such an advantage for learning so much in my life. This was pre-pandemic so people still sort of spoke on flights. I’d listen to these older people share their regrets as I was on my way to sit and work a job that made my soul feel dead. Every part of my soul knew this wasn’t aligned. ✈️😢

Every single older person shared with me that they wished they lived their youth. That they traveled. Didn’t care as much what people think. Spent more time with friends and family. Had more fun. 💫

I’d either cry on spot or go to the bathroom upon landing and sob. It was emotionally heavy but shook me to realize how fragile life is and that it must be lived. 🙏🏽

Now I’ve made it my purpose to live intentionally and share these messages with everyone I can. Live in alignment with your hearts calling! Each moment you think you’ll just put it off for tomorrow accumulates to weeks, months, years of no action. Nobody is going to save you, it has to ultimately come from within. 📆🌟

Here’s to living YOUR most extraordinary life. 🫶🏽✨

A comment I get from time to time asks how I am always happy. 🤔❓

And while it may appear on social media that I am always happy, it is not the full picture. Yes, there is truth to it that most often when I am in epic destinations or on adventures with friends or solo, I am so stoked on life. It’s hard not to be when experiencing that magic.🪄 

But honestly, my aim isn’t to always be happy but instead to live every day of life in a beautiful state. Grateful for all emotions, making my baseline gratitude. I’ve been going through battles I’ll probably never share on social media and it’s your reminder that every person you meet is going through something. Always be kind. 🙌🏽

When the battles get tough, I have a toolkit of things I love to do to process and pull myself out of those situations. Here’s some of my list and I hope it can help you!⬇️

1. Wellness: Mindful meditation, breathwork, yoga, movement. They help me to stay grounded and connect with my inner peace. Emotions = energy in motion. Movement allows for flow. 
2. Nature: Hiking, surfing, or just being active outdoors in the mountains or ocean. Nature is healing and rejuvenates my soul. 🏔️🌊
3. Photography: Capturing moments, big or small, helps me appreciate the beauty and magic in the world. 
4. Community: Spending time with friends & family. We are social creatures.
5. Journaling: Journaling and reflecting on my thoughts helps me process. 

It's OK to not be okay. It's okay to have tough days. What's important is how we handle those days and what we do to bring ourselves back to a state of joy and gratitude. I’m sharing this because I want you to know that you're not alone. We all have our struggles and it's through sharing that we can support each other, learn, and grow.

Happy to be in this Kiwi Surf Town, Raglan, on the North Island of New Zealand. Its so cute here. When I traveled in the past, I used to travel for the best mountains to hike, because I loved hiking more than anything. But now, I think I might love surfing more than hiking…🙊 so I’ve been sort of planning my travels around fun surfing spots. And this is my first stop of the year! Thankfully New Zealand has both - mountains and ocean! 🌊🏄 

I’ll be honest with you, surfing still intimidates me. I took my first surf lesson when I studied abroad in Australia in 2017 and since then, surfed a few times and took a few lessons when I lived in Hawaii but I still had a lot of fear revolving around it. Then the surf camp in Bali last year helped me a lot! The power of the ocean is so humbling for me. I can hike for days, mountaineer, be on crazy cliffs and feel close to no fear, but the ocean, and surfing in powerful waves specifically, feels outside my comfort zone. 

I dance the line of challenging myself and knowing my limits. Life’s a dance. I love to try new things because thats how you learn and grow! I feel the discomfort each time before I paddle out but afterwards, I feel so amazing from challenging myself and growing!
